            <fr:title text="Modus ponens">Modus ponens</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>26</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/0085/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0085</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/0085/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Modus ponens">Modus ponens</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>        An argument is an instance of <html:strong>modus ponens</html:strong> when it has the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \rightarrow  B, A \;/\; B]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>So, for example, the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \land  \neg  r) \rightarrow  (s \lor  r), p \land  \neg  r \;/\; s \lor  r]]></fr:tex> is an instance of modus ponens.
        One thing many thinkers take as a constraint on a good theory of implication is that every instance of modus ponens should come out to be valid.
        Suppose that the premises <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \land  \neg  r) \rightarrow  (s \lor  r)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  \neg  r]]></fr:tex> hold.
        Since we've supposed that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  \neg  r]]></fr:tex> holds, it seems that everything it implies should also hold.
        And we've supposed that it implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s \lor  r]]></fr:tex>.
        Thus, it seems to many that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s \lor  r]]></fr:tex> must follow from these premises.
</html:p>
            <html:p>       Classical logic validates modus ponens---by which I mean that it validates <html:em>every</html:em> instance of modus ponens.
       Recall that implication works in the Boolean structure according to this table:
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>21</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/003M/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>003M</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/003M/</fr:route>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
  <html:thead><html:tr>
    <html:td class="topedge leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  </html:tr></html:thead>
  <html:tbody>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>        Since we arrive at classical logic by using the matrix that designates just <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> in this structure, to have a classical counterexample to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q, p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex>, we would need to assign both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> while assigning <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>; as the above table shows, this is not possible.
        So <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q, p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex> is valid in classical logic, and since classical logic is substitution invariant, this means that all instances of modus ponens are classically valid as well.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        Now, in the strong Kleene structure, implication works according to this table:
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005Q/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>005Q</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/005Q/</fr:route>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
  <html:thead><html:tr>
    <html:td class="topedge leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  </html:tr></html:thead>
  <html:tbody>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>        If we designate just <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> to reach the logic K3, you can see that the reasoning works just as in classical logic: there is no strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p \rightarrow  q) = v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, but where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(q) \neq  \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>.
        So <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q, p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex> is valid in K3 as well.
        However, things are different when it comes to LP.
        Recall that LP can be specified by a matrix that uses the strong Kleene structure, but with both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> counting as designated values.
        Then there is a valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>; that gives us <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p \rightarrow  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> by the above table.
        So <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w]]></fr:tex> is a counterexample to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q, p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex>, and thus modus ponens is not valid in LP.
        As FDE is weaker than LP, this means that modus ponens must not be valid in FDE either.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        When it comes to NJ, the reasoning around modus ponens is different.
        For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, there is a proof of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \rightarrow  B, A \;/\; B]]></fr:tex>, consisting of just assumptions of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \rightarrow  B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, followed by a single step of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow  E]]></fr:tex>.
        For example, the following proof is a proof of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q, p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex>:</html:p>
            <html:p>
              <fr:resource hash="5d3b72cfa90aa250822f09313c329df0">
                <fr:resource-content>
                  <html:img src="/lectures/5d3b72cfa90aa250822f09313c329df0.svg" />
                </fr:resource-content>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{p \rightarrow  q\vphantom{|}}}
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{p\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  E:\quad }}
            \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{q\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP]]></fr:resource-source>
              </fr:resource>
            </html:p>
            <html:p>As this same idea would work for any other sentences, every instance of modus ponens is valid in minimal logic, and thus in intuitionistic and classical logics as well.
        So minimal and intuitionistic logics are like classical logic and K3, and unlike LP and FDE in this regard.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
